Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

In a large #bowl{}, add the garlic, @British chicken breasts{2}, @korma curry paste{50%g} and half the @low fat natural yoghurt{75%g}. Season with @salt{}, then mix to coat the chicken in the marinade. Set aside.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Meanwhile, chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel).

Halve the @green pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Chop into 2cm chunks.

Pop the potato chunks onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @olive oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then sprinkle over the @tandoori masala mix{1%sachet}.

Toss to coat, then spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the middle shelf until golden, ~{30-40%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, pop the pepper chunks onto one side of a large baking tray. Drizzle with @oil{}, then season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Toss to coat.

Lay the marinated chicken flat onto the other side of the same tray as the pepper.

Roast on the top shelf of your oven until the pepper is golden and the chicken is cooked through, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

While everything bakes, halve the @baby plum tomatoes{125%g} and pop them into a small bowl.

Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then stir through the @olive oil{1/2%tbsp} for the dressing. Set aside.

When the chicken and veg are cooked, slice the chicken into 2cm thick slices, then share between your plates.

Serve the roasted peppers and spiced potatoes alongside. Spoon over the tomatoes.

Finish with a drizzle of the remaining yoghurt.

Enjoy!